<h1>
Visual C++ Does Not Rebuild After Modifying Header
</h1>
<h2>SYMPTOMS</h2>
<p>
The Microsoft Visual C++ <code>Build</code> command does not re-compile
any sources even though a header file in the project was modified.
<h2>CAUSE</h2>
<p>
Microsoft Visual C++ fails to record dependency information when
preprocessing is performed separately from compiling, as
BullseyeCoverage does.
<h2>RESOLUTION</h2>
<p>
After modifying a header, rebuild your whole project.
<h2>MORE INFORMATION</h2>
<p>
The Microsoft Visual C++ compiler generates dependency information into
a file named <i>project</i>.pdb during preprocessing.
BullseyeCoverage feeds the compiler preprocessed source files.
Microsoft Visual C++ records only dependency information for the main
source file but not the header files named by <code>#line</code>
directives.
<p>
Microsoft does not document the <code>.pdb</code> file format,
so BullseyeCoverage cannot work around the problem by updating the file
with the correct dependencies.
<p>
The problem does not occur with Microsoft Visual C++ version 6.

